  <section class="section methodology" data-tab="underhood">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header-editorial">
        <div>
          <div class="kicker">Methodology</div>
          <h2>How the numbers are made</h2>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="methodology-body">
        <div class="method-block">
          <h3>Cross-model divergence score</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">For each prompt across the three active engines, Drift Radar takes the own-brand visibility on every engine, then combines the range and the Coefficient of Variation into a single score in <code>[0, 1]</code>:</p>
          <pre class="formula">divergence = 0.7 · (max(vis) − min(vis)) + 0.3 · clamp(CV(vis), 0, 2) / 2</pre>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">Range dominates – intuitive and bounded. CV adds a secondary smoothed signal for cases where all engines are non-zero but still spread. Scores ≥ 0.30 are flagged as drifting.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="method-block">
          <h3>Wilson 95 % confidence intervals</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">Every visibility fraction is a proportion from a small sample – Peec samples once per day per engine. Drift Radar reports Wilson score confidence intervals for each prompt × engine: three days means <code>n = 3</code>, so bands are wide. Small samples get wide bands; the tool never overstates certainty.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="method-block">
          <h3>Silence classification</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;"><strong class="serif">Own-only silence</strong> – your brand has zero mentions on every engine, and at least one tracked competitor has at least one mention on some engine.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;"><strong class="serif">Full silence</strong> – no tracked brand, own or competitor, is mentioned on any engine. The category is answered generically.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="method-block">
          <h3>Narrative stability extraction</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">For the maximum-drift prompts, Drift Radar calls <code>Claude Haiku 4.5</code> over the full response text from every engine and extracts up to five atomic claims per answer, each categorized as <em>brand</em>, <em>substance</em>, <em>function</em>, <em>condition</em>, or <em>criterion</em>.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">The narrative-mix bar shows claim-type distribution per engine. <em>Brand</em> claims rarely overlap across engines – each model names different products. <em>Substance</em> and <em>criterion</em> claims overlap more often (MSM, Glucosamin, grain-free), because active ingredients and quality markers are closer to settled knowledge. Stable concepts become the anchor for content briefs; divergent ones mark the editorial gaps.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="method-block">
          <h3>Data source</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">Peec AI MCP at <code>api.peec.ai/mcp</code>, OAuth authenticated.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">Tools used: <code>list_prompts</code>, <code>list_chats</code>, <code>get_brand_report</code> with <code>dimensions=[prompt_id, model_id]</code>, <code>get_chat</code> for full response text.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 8px;">Active engines in this snapshot: {active_models.map((m: any) => m.name).join(', ')}.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section limitations" data-tab="underhood">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header-editorial">
        <div>
          <div class="kicker">What this report is not</div>
          <h2>Limitations &amp; honest caveats</h2>
          <p class="caption" style="margin-top: 12px; max-width: 720px;">
            The divergence score is a ranking signal, not a forecasting model. Three directions where the numbers deserve scepticism before they drive an investment decision.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="limit-grid">
        <div class="limit-card">
          <div class="limit-kicker">Sample size</div>
          <h3 class="limit-title">Three-day window, N ≈ 3</h3>
          <p class="limit-body">Peec samples each prompt × engine once per day. A three-day snapshot gives N = 3 chats per cell – the Wilson 95 % CIs are correspondingly wide (often spanning 0 – 0.56 for a zero-visibility cell). Use the score for ranking and triage, re-measure weekly before acting on a single-prompt shift. All CI values are in <code>drift_radar.json → prompts[].wilson_ci_by_model</code>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="limit-card">
          <div class="limit-kicker">Prompt design</div>
          <h3 class="limit-title">50 prompts, one category</h3>
          <p class="limit-body">The Pferdegold prompt list covers seven topics around horse supplement feed. The 12.1× engine spread is category-specific – AI Overview happens to retrieve Amazon product pages directly for this vertical, which tilts visibility. The method generalises across verticals; the specific ratios do not. Run Drift Radar on your own prompt list before quoting the aggregate.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="limit-card">
          <div class="limit-kicker">Claim extraction</div>
          <h3 class="limit-title">Haiku reads transcript text</h3>
          <p class="limit-body">Stable-vs-divergent claim tags come from Claude Haiku 4.5 parsing the chat transcript text into five types. Spot checks are good, but this is a directional narrative signal – not a factual validator. Ingredient names and quality markers overlap more than brand names because active ingredients are closer to settled knowledge; this is an LLM reading other LLMs, not an authoritative source.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="limit-card">
          <div class="limit-kicker">Engine coverage</div>
          <h3 class="limit-title">Three engines – ChatGPT, Gemini, AI Overview</h3>
          <p class="limit-body">Peec's Pro plan tracks three engines in parallel; Perplexity, Copilot and Claude web are not in this snapshot. The engine-spread ratio would move when the engine set changes. When comparing runs, hold the engine set constant.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section underhood" data-tab="underhood">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header-editorial">
        <div>
          <div class="kicker">Under the hood</div>
          <h2>From MCP call to static page</h2>
          <p class="caption" style="margin-top: 12px; max-width: 720px;">
            Drift Radar is a four-step pipeline. Peec MCP supplies the raw brand and chat data, a Python script folds it into divergence scores, Claude Haiku 4.5 lifts the narrative claims out of every response, and Astro renders the whole report as a static page. Every step below is quoted verbatim from the actual implementation.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="underhood-steps">
        <div class="underhood-step">
          <div class="underhood-step-head">
            <span class="underhood-step-num">01</span>
            <h3>Pull the data from Peec MCP</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="underhood-step-dek">Four MCP tools, authenticated via the Peec OAuth connector. <code>get_brand_report</code> with <code>dimensions=[prompt_id, model_id]</code> is the one that produces the matrix the whole dashboard is built on.</p>
          <pre class="underhood-code">{`# Project lookup
list_projects() → [{ id: "or_1caa...", name: "Pferdegold", status: "TRIAL" }]

# Prompt universe (50 prompts)
list_prompts(project_id="or_1caa...") → pr_f430..., pr_ce22..., ...

# The core matrix: own-brand visibility per prompt × engine
get_brand_report(
    project_id = "or_1caa...",
    brand_id   = "kw_751e...",              # Pferdegold
    start_date = "2026-04-20",
    end_date   = "2026-04-22",
    dimensions = ["prompt_id", "model_id"],
) → { columns: [...], rows: [...] }

# Full response text for narrative extraction
list_chats(project_id="...", prompt_id="pr_f430...", ...)
get_chat(chat_id="ch_d5ff...") → { messages, brands_mentioned, sources }`}</pre>
        </div>

        <div class="underhood-step">
          <div class="underhood-step-head">
            <span class="underhood-step-num">02</span>
            <h3>Compute divergence and silence in Python</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="underhood-step-dek">The matrix becomes a drift score per prompt: weighted combination of visibility range and Coefficient of Variation. Silence is classified as <em>own-only</em> (competitors present, own brand absent) or <em>full</em> (nobody named).</p>
          <pre class="underhood-code">{`def compute_prompt_metrics(per_model, active_models):
    vis_vals = [per_model[m]["visibility"] if m in per_model else 0
                for m in active_models]
    range_vis = max(vis_vals) - min(vis_vals)
    cv_vis    = pstdev(vis_vals) / mean(vis_vals) if mean(vis_vals) else 0

    divergence_score = round(
        0.7 * range_vis + 0.3 * min(cv_vis, 2.0) / 2.0, 3
    )

    return {
        "visibility_by_model": {m: per_model[m]["visibility"]
                                for m in active_models if m in per_model},
        "divergence_score": divergence_score,
        "range_visibility": range_vis,
        "cv_visibility":    cv_vis,
        "own_silence":      max(vis_vals) == 0,
    }`}</pre>
        </div>

        <div class="underhood-step">
          <div class="underhood-step-head">
            <span class="underhood-step-num">03</span>
            <h3>Extract narrative claims with Haiku 4.5</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="underhood-step-dek">Every assistant response goes through Claude Haiku 4.5 with a strict JSON-only system prompt. Five typed claims per chat – brand, substance, function, condition, criterion – with verbatim evidence quotes for auditability.</p>
          <pre class="underhood-code">{`SYSTEM = (
  "You extract structured claims from AI-generated product "
  "recommendations. Return ONLY valid JSON, no prose, "
  "no markdown fencing. Never include \\\`\\\`\\\`json."
)

USER = f"""User query to an AI search engine: {query!r}

The AI engine responded with:
\\"\\"\\"{response_text}\\"\\"\\"

Extract up to 5 atomic claims. For each claim, categorize:
- brand      : specific product or brand name
- substance  : active ingredient (Glucosamin, MSM, ...)
- function   : functional benefit (supports joints, ...)
- condition  : health condition or use case (arthrose, ...)
- criterion  : quality/selection criterion (sugar-free, ...)

Return a JSON array of up to 5 objects:
{{ "text": "...", "type": "...", "evidence": "<verbatim quote>" }}"""

# Model: claude-haiku-4-5-20251001
# Temperature: default (1.0); strict JSON-only output,
# fenced retries with exponential backoff on 429/503/529.`}</pre>
        </div>

        <div class="underhood-step">
          <div class="underhood-step-head">
            <span class="underhood-step-num">04</span>
            <h3>Render as a static Astro page</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="underhood-step-dek">No runtime fetching, no server. The Python pipeline writes a single <code>drift_radar.json</code>; Astro imports it, ships a static bundle to Cloudflare Pages. Everything you see on this page is pre-rendered at build time from that JSON.</p>
          <pre class="underhood-code">{`---
// src/pages/index.astro
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import data from '../data/drift_radar.json';

const { summary, prompts, competitors, active_models } = data;
const sortedPrompts = [...prompts].sort(
  (a, b) => b.divergence_score - a.divergence_score
);
const deepDives = sortedPrompts.filter(p => p.chat_sample);
---

<Base title={\`Drift Radar – \${data.own_brand}\`}>
  <!-- Hero, Key Visual, Numbers, Heatmap,
       Deep Dives, Competitive Landscape, ... -->
</Base>`}</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="caption" style="margin-top: 40px; max-width: 780px;">
        Nothing is hidden. The JSON that drives the entire dashboard is downloadable from the export bar above. So is the CSV version for spreadsheets. Every claim, every divergence score, every MCP call can be reproduced by another operator in under an hour.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

